Soultions

For this assignment, we will use the forecast and tseries libraries.

library("forecast")
library("tseries")

The dataset is the exchange rate for the Indian Rupee to 1 U.S. Dollar. The data is daily from July 1st, 2002 to April 8th, 2011.

data <- read.csv("http://ptrckprry.com/course/forecasting/data/rupee.csv")
date <- as.Date(data$date, format="%m/%d/%Y")
time <- 1:length(date)
rupee <- data$rupee

We will work with the logs of the exchange rates:

log.rupee <- log(rupee)

Problem 1

Here is a time series plot of log.rupee, along with the ACF and PACF:

plot(date, log.rupee, type="l")

Acf(log.rupee)

Pacf(log.rupee)

Here is the first difference, along with the ACF and PACF:

diff.log.rupee <- c(NA, diff(log.rupee))
plot(date, diff.log.rupee, type="l")

Acf(diff.log.rupee)

Pacf(diff.log.rupee)

Here is the second difference, along with the ACF and PACF:

diff2.log.rupee <- c(NA, diff(diff.log.rupee))
plot(date, diff2.log.rupee, type="l")

Acf(diff2.log.rupee)

Pacf(diff2.log.rupee)

Does the series appear to be stationary?

The first difference looks stationary, but not the original series.

Can you identify an ARIMA(p,d,q) model from these plots?

Possibly an ARIMA(12,1,0) or an ARIMA(0,1,12).

Problem 2

Here are the AICc for all ARIMA(p,1,q) models without constant for p and q ranging from 0 to 2:

# Hint: you can modify the code from
# http://ptrckprry.com/course/forecasting/lecture/nasdaq-arch.html
# if you don't want to do this by hand.

d <- 1
for (p in 0:2) {
    for (q in 0:2) {
        # manually difference to avoid bug in Arima code
        fit <- Arima(diff.log.rupee, c(p,0,q), include.constant=FALSE)
        cat("ARIMA", "(", p, ",", d, ",", q, ")",
            " : ", fit$aicc, "\n", sep="")
    }
}

Select an ARIMA(p,1,q) model.

Based on AICc, we select p = 1 and q = 0.

Problem 3

Here is a plot of the residuals:

plot(date, resid, type="l")

Here are an ACF and PACF of the residuals:

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
Acf(resid)
Pacf(resid)

Here are an ACF and PACF of the squared residuals:

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
Acf(resid^2)
Pacf(resid^2)

Use these plots to argue that the residuals, although approximately uncorrelated, are not independent; instead, they show evidence of conditional heteroscedasticity.

The ACF and PACF of the residuals show some nonzero autocorrelation, especially at lag 11, but it is very small (less than 0.07 in absolute value); the residuals are approximately uncorrelated.

From the ACF and PACF of the squared residuals, we can see noticeable correlations and partial autocorrelations at lags 1 and 10, indicating autocorrelation in the volatility. We can also see this volatility behavior in the time series plot.

Problem 4

Here are the AICc values for the ARCH(q):

q <- 0:10
loglik <- rep(NA, length(q))
N <- length(resid)

for (i in 1:length(q)) {
    if (q[i] == 0) {
        loglik[i] <- -0.5 * N * (1 + log(2 * pi * mean(resid^2)))
    } else {
        fit <- garch(resid, c(0,q[i]), trace=FALSE)
        loglik[i] <- logLik(fit)
    }
}
## Warning in sqrt(pred$e): NaNs produced
k <- q + 1
aicc <- -2 * loglik  + 2 * k * N / (N - k - 1)

print(data.frame(q, loglik, aicc))

Comment on the statistical significance of the parameter values of your selected model.

The parameters are all highly statistically significant. (This is not particularly relevant, because the statistical tests on the coefficients are only valid if the model is correct.)

Write the complete form of the ARCH or GARCH model you have selected.

The conditional variance of the shock is

h[t] = (5.558e-08) + (1.327e-01) * (eps[t-1])^2 + (8.859e-01) * (h[t-1])

Problem 5

Construct a 95% one step ahead forecast interval for the log exchange rate, based on your ARIMA-ARCH model.

# h <- omega + alpha * r0^2
f1 <- (3.78673) # from Problem 2
h1 <- (5.558e-08) + (1.327e-01) * (-0.0007984057)^2 + (8.859e-01) * (1.095315e-05)

f1 + c(-1.96, 1.96) * sqrt(h1)
## [1] 3.780581 3.792879

Compare this to the interval based on the ARIMA only model from Problem 2.

The ARIMA-only interval from Problem 2 is (3.777838, 3.795622). The ARIMA-ARCH interval is narrower, because its width is adaptive.

plot(date, ht, type="l")

Use this plot to locate bursts of high volatility.

There is particularly high volatility in the beginning of 2007 and in late 2008 to early 2009.

Do these highly volatile periods agree with those found from examination of the time series plot of the log exchange rates themselves?

Yes, the time series plot varies more during these time periods.

Problem 7

Here is a time series plot which simultaneously shows the log exchange rates, together with the ARIMA-ARCH one-step-ahead 95% forecast intervals based on information available in the previous day:

plot(date, log.rupee, type="l")
lines(date, f + 1.96 * sqrt(ht), lty=2, col=2)
lines(date, f - 1.96 * sqrt(ht), lty=2, col=2)

Using this plot, comment on the accuracy and practical usefulness of the forecast intervals.

The forecast interval seems accurate. One nice practical feature is that the width is adaptive: the interval is wider in periods of high volatility, and narrower in periods of low volatility.

Problem 8

Here is a normal probability plot of the ARCH residuals.

resid.arch <- resid / sqrt(ht)
qqnorm(resid.arch)
qqline(resid.arch)

Does the model seem to have adequately described the leptokurtosis (long-tailedness) in the data?

The model is not capturing the leptokurtosis; the tails of the arch residuals are wider than those of a Gaussian random variable.

Problem 9

Here is a count of how many prediction interval failures there were:

sum(abs(resid.arch) > 1.96, na.rm=TRUE)
## [1] 113

The number of prediction intervals is:

sum(!is.na(resid.arch))
## [1] 2229

**What percentage of the time did the intervals fail?

The proportion of intervals that failed was

100 * (113 / 2229)
## [1] 5.069538

That is, the intervals failed roughly 5% of the time.
